<HEADLINE>
<P>
DAY RUNNER INCOME DASHES UP 26.7% IN RECORD-BREAKING '93 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG JOHNSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Day Runner Inc. on Monday credited a strong fourth quarter and increased 
business from wholesale clubs and large office product retailers for record 
1993 sales and earnings. 
</P>
<P>
 Net income rose by 26.7% to $5.6 million, or 93 cents per share, up from $4.5 
million, or 77 cents per share, a year earlier.Revenue rose to $81.9 million 
last year from $71.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
 Earnings during the unusually strong fourth quarter rose by 71.6% to $3.2 
million. Fourth-quarter revenue rose to $32.3 million, up from $22.8 million a 
year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
 "The fourth quarter of 1993 was the best quarter in Day Runner's history," 
said Mark Vidovich, Day Runner chairman and chief executive. "We believe that 
the solid groundwork we laid earlier in 1993 paid off during the crucial last 
three months of the year." 
</P>
<P>
 While Day Runner historically reports strong second and fourth quarters, the 
final reporting period of 1993 was driven by "significant growth in our sales 
to mass market customers, including wholesale clubs, the office products 
super-store channel and international customers," Vidovich said. 
</P>
<P>
 In a related move, Day Runner changed its fiscal year end from Dec. 31 to June 
30. The change will "allow us to to do our intensive business planning during 
our less busy season," Vidovich said. The company will report a six-month 
fiscal year ending June 30, and begin the 1995 fiscal year on July 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Day Runner manufactures and markets paper-based personal organizers for the 
retail market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
