<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; BASKETS CARRY LOVE, HOUSEHOLD GOODIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Laguna Fire Relief Coalition began the pleasant task Monday of 
distributing Valentine's Day baskets, stuffed with items as unexpected as a 
tiny television and as practical as a fly swatter, to victims of the October 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
 "Is it Christmas?" asked one man, shaking his head as he bent to examine first 
one cellophane-wrapped package and then another. 
</P>
<P>
 Even coalition workers seemed stunned by the weekend delivery of more than 100 
baskets, tubs, planters and other containers bulging with goodies, from spices 
and cookbooks to gift wrapping and radios. The packages were prepared by the 
Junior League of Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 "When we first heard they were going to put together treat baskets, we were 
thinking candy hearts," director Anita Mangels said. "This stuff is amazing." 
</P>
<P>
 For some fire survivors, the toughest job Monday appeared to be deciding which 
package to choose. 
</P>
<P>
 Reah Travis, who lost her Canyon Acres home in the firestorm, settled on a 
basket laden with household supplies, including dish towels and toothbrushes, 
and topped with a pink bow. 
</P>
<P>
 "I can't even believe it . . . what people do for other people," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Shannon Zech, president-elect of the Junior League of Orange County, which has 
helped fire victims since shortly after the firestorm, said the group's new 
members took on this latest project. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were looking for other ways we could help," she said. The new members 
"really took it and ran with it and put it all together." 
</P>
<P>
 The Laguna Fire Relief Coalition provides a variety of assistance for fire 
survivors from its headquarters in the Boat Canyon shopping center, including 
crisis counseling, food, clothing and referrals to other support agencies. 
</P>
<P>
 The baskets will be distributed throughout the week, until they are gone. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're going to go pretty darn fast and today will be the big kickoff day," 
Mangels said Monday. "Our survivors are just going to be crazy about this 
stuff." 
</P>
<P>
 Outside the coalition office, former Canyon Acres resident Betty Watkins 
wrestled a bulky basket filled with crayons, greeting cards and noodles into 
her Toyota. 
</P>
<P>
 "I chose this one because it had a cordless screwdriver in it and I've been 
missing it," she said. LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</TEXT>
