<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; NATIONWIDE; ANTIBODY IS USED TO FIGHT PNEUMONIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Researchers from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases and 
the Scripps Research Institute said they have successfully used human antibody 
fragments in mice to fight a common pneumonia virus.The study was published in 
the latest Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. Pieces of human 
antibody were used to treat mice for respiratory syncytial virus, the major 
worldwide cause of pneumonia in infants and children. Single doses applied by 
nasal spray over three days completely cured the infection, the researchers 
said. It may be eventually possible to develop antibody treatments for other 
viral infections, including influenza and the common cold, researchers said. 
</P>
